{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":868,"text":"When I was a young boy,"},{"time":2654,"text":"I used to gaze through the microscope of my father"},{"time":5262,"text":"at the insects in amber that he kept in the house."},{"time":8620,"text":"And they were remarkably well preserved,"},{"time":11177,"text":"morphologically just phenomenal."},{"time":13422,"text":"And we used to imagine that someday,"},{"time":15616,"text":"they would actually come to life"},{"time":17225,"text":"and they would crawl out of the resin,"},{"time":19222,"text":"and, if they could, they would fly away."}]},{"cues":[{"time":21966,"text":"If you had asked me 10 years ago whether or not"},{"time":24342,"text":"we would ever be able to sequence the genome of extinct animals,"},{"time":27540,"text":"I would have told you, it's unlikely."},{"time":30015,"text":"If you had asked whether or not we would actually be able"},{"time":31910,"text":"to revive an extinct species,"},{"time":34062,"text":"I would have said, pipe dream."},{"time":35721,"text":"But I'm actually standing here today, amazingly,"},{"time":38246,"text":"to tell you that not only is the sequencing"},{"time":40253,"text":"of extinct genomes a possibility, actually a modern-day reality,"},{"time":44443,"text":"but the revival of an extinct species is actually within reach,"},{"time":48736,"text":"maybe not from the insects in amber --"},{"time":50575,"text":"in fact, this mosquito was actually used"},{"time":52535,"text":"for the inspiration for \"Jurassic Park\" â€”"},{"time":54887,"text":"but from woolly mammoths, the well preserved remains"},{"time":57447,"text":"of woolly mammoths in the permafrost."}]},{"cues":[{"time":59654,"text":"Woollies are a particularly interesting,"},{"time":61727,"text":"quintessential image of the Ice Age."},{"time":64273,"text":"They were large. They were hairy."},{"time":66098,"text":"They had large tusks, and we seem to have"},{"time":68082,"text":"a very deep connection with them, like we do with elephants."},{"time":70982,"text":"Maybe it's because elephants share"},{"time":73497,"text":"many things in common with us."},{"time":75319,"text":"They bury their dead. They educate the next of kin."},{"time":78047,"text":"They have social knits that are very close."},{"time":81067,"text":"Or maybe it's actually because we're bound by deep time,"},{"time":83937,"text":"because elephants, like us, share their origins in Africa"},{"time":87275,"text":"some seven million years ago,"},{"time":89398,"text":"and as habitats changed and environments changed,"},{"time":92192,"text":"we actually, like the elephants, migrated out"},{"time":95802,"text":"into Europe and Asia."}]},{"cues":[{"time":98022,"text":"So the first large mammoth that appears on the scene"},{"time":100725,"text":"is meridionalis, which was standing four meters tall"},{"time":104131,"text":"weighing about 10 tons, and was a woodland-adapted species"},{"time":107963,"text":"and spread from Western Europe clear across Central Asia,"},{"time":110925,"text":"across the Bering land bridge"},{"time":113175,"text":"and into parts of North America."},{"time":115485,"text":"And then, again, as climate changed as it always does,"},{"time":118173,"text":"and new habitats opened up,"},{"time":119683,"text":"we had the arrival of a steppe-adapted species"},{"time":122159,"text":"called trogontherii in Central Asia"},{"time":124407,"text":"pushing meridionalis out into Western Europe."},{"time":127157,"text":"And the open grassland savannas of North America"},{"time":129552,"text":"opened up, leading to the Columbian mammoth,"},{"time":131712,"text":"a large, hairless species in North America."},{"time":134252,"text":"And it was really only about 500,000 years later"},{"time":137163,"text":"that we had the arrival of the woolly,"},{"time":139868,"text":"the one that we all know and love so much,"},{"time":141896,"text":"spreading from an East Beringian point of origin"},{"time":145206,"text":"across Central Asia, again pushing the trogontherii"},{"time":148092,"text":"out through Central Europe,"},{"time":149743,"text":"and over hundreds of thousands of years"},{"time":151809,"text":"migrating back and forth across the Bering land bridge"},{"time":154893,"text":"during times of glacial peaks"},{"time":156920,"text":"and coming into direct contact"},{"time":158716,"text":"with the Columbian relatives living in the south,"},{"time":161520,"text":"and there they survive over hundreds of thousands of years"},{"time":164808,"text":"during traumatic climatic shifts."},{"time":166985,"text":"So there's a highly plastic animal dealing with great transitions"},{"time":171201,"text":"in temperature and environment, and doing very, very well."},{"time":174049,"text":"And there they survive on the mainland until about 10,000 years ago,"},{"time":178040,"text":"and actually, surprisingly, on the small islands off of Siberia"},{"time":181193,"text":"and Alaska until about 3,000 years ago."},{"time":183667,"text":"So Egyptians are building pyramids"},{"time":185356,"text":"and woollies are still living on islands."}]},{"cues":[{"time":188122,"text":"And then they disappear."},{"time":189671,"text":"Like 99 percent of all the animals that have once lived,"},{"time":191925,"text":"they go extinct, likely due to a warming climate"},{"time":195204,"text":"and fast-encroaching dense forests"},{"time":197286,"text":"that are migrating north,"},{"time":198787,"text":"and also, as the late, great Paul Martin once put it,"},{"time":201760,"text":"probably Pleistocene overkill,"},{"time":203511,"text":"so the large game hunters that took them down."}]},{"cues":[{"time":206084,"text":"Fortunately, we find millions of their remains"},{"time":208346,"text":"strewn across the permafrost buried deep"},{"time":211023,"text":"in Siberia and Alaska, and we can actually go up there"},{"time":214148,"text":"and actually take them out."},{"time":216058,"text":"And the preservation is, again,"},{"time":217582,"text":"like those insects in [amber], phenomenal."},{"time":220152,"text":"So you have teeth, bones with blood"},{"time":223672,"text":"which look like blood, you have hair,"},{"time":225712,"text":"and you have intact carcasses or heads"},{"time":227239,"text":"which still have brains in them."}]},{"cues":[{"time":230182,"text":"So the preservation and the survival of DNA"},{"time":232553,"text":"depends on many factors, and I have to admit,"},{"time":234625,"text":"most of which we still don't quite understand,"},{"time":236953,"text":"but depending upon when an organism dies"},{"time":239025,"text":"and how quickly he's buried, the depth of that burial,"},{"time":243514,"text":"the constancy of the temperature of that burial environment,"},{"time":246816,"text":"will ultimately dictate how long DNA will survive"},{"time":249384,"text":"over geologically meaningful time frames."},{"time":252245,"text":"And it's probably surprising to many of you"},{"time":253889,"text":"sitting in this room that it's not the time that matters,"},{"time":257029,"text":"it's not the length of preservation,"},{"time":258656,"text":"it's the consistency of the temperature of that preservation that matters most."}]},{"cues":[{"time":262638,"text":"So if we were to go deep now within the bones"},{"time":265457,"text":"and the teeth that actually survived the fossilization process,"},{"time":268432,"text":"the DNA which was once intact, tightly wrapped"},{"time":271824,"text":"around histone proteins, is now under attack"},{"time":274192,"text":"by the bacteria that lived symbiotically with the mammoth"},{"time":277158,"text":"for years during its lifetime."},{"time":278968,"text":"So those bacteria, along with the environmental bacteria,"},{"time":282169,"text":"free water and oxygen, actually break apart the DNA"},{"time":285872,"text":"into smaller and smaller and smaller DNA fragments,"},{"time":288417,"text":"until all you have are fragments that range"},{"time":290738,"text":"from 10 base pairs to, in the best case scenarios,"},{"time":293419,"text":"a few hundred base pairs in length."},{"time":295792,"text":"So most fossils out there in the fossil record"},{"time":298103,"text":"are actually completely devoid of all organic signatures."},{"time":300816,"text":"But a few of them actually have DNA fragments"},{"time":303249,"text":"that survive for thousands,"},{"time":305123,"text":"even a few millions of years in time."},{"time":308872,"text":"And using state-of-the-art clean room technology,"},{"time":311060,"text":"we've devised ways that we can actually pull these DNAs"},{"time":313724,"text":"away from all the rest of the gunk in there,"},{"time":316228,"text":"and it's not surprising to any of you sitting in the room"},{"time":318427,"text":"that if I take a mammoth bone or a tooth"},{"time":320548,"text":"and I extract its DNA that I'll get mammoth DNA,"},{"time":323547,"text":"but I'll also get all the bacteria that once lived with the mammoth,"},{"time":327358,"text":"and, more complicated, I'll get all the DNA"},{"time":329605,"text":"that survived in that environment with it,"},{"time":331789,"text":"so the bacteria, the fungi, and so on and so forth."},{"time":334963,"text":"Not surprising then again that a mammoth"},{"time":337368,"text":"preserved in the permafrost will have something"},{"time":339040,"text":"on the order of 50 percent of its DNA being mammoth,"},{"time":341908,"text":"whereas something like the Columbian mammoth,"},{"time":343931,"text":"living in a temperature and buried in a temperate environment"},{"time":346548,"text":"over its laying-in will only have 3 to 10 percent endogenous."}]},{"cues":[{"time":350365,"text":"But we've come up with very clever ways"},{"time":352808,"text":"that we can actually discriminate, capture and discriminate,"},{"time":355914,"text":"the mammoth from the non-mammoth DNA,"},{"time":357889,"text":"and with the advances in high-throughput sequencing,"},{"time":360439,"text":"we can actually pull out and bioinformatically"},{"time":363276,"text":"re-jig all these small mammoth fragments"},{"time":366245,"text":"and place them onto a backbone"},{"time":368542,"text":"of an Asian or African elephant chromosome."},{"time":371101,"text":"And so by doing that, we can actually get all the little points"},{"time":373677,"text":"that discriminate between a mammoth and an Asian elephant,"},{"time":376502,"text":"and what do we know, then, about a mammoth?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":379541,"text":"Well, the mammoth genome is almost at full completion,"},{"time":382694,"text":"and we know that it's actually really big. It's mammoth."},{"time":386235,"text":"So a hominid genome is about three billion base pairs,"},{"time":389420,"text":"but an elephant and mammoth genome"},{"time":390997,"text":"is about two billion base pairs larger, and most of that"},{"time":393653,"text":"is composed of small, repetitive DNAs"},{"time":396277,"text":"that make it very difficult to actually re-jig the entire structure of the genome."}]},{"cues":[{"time":400910,"text":"So having this information allows us to answer"},{"time":403271,"text":"one of the interesting relationship questions"},{"time":405406,"text":"between mammoths and their living relatives,"},{"time":407578,"text":"the African and the Asian elephant,"},{"time":409622,"text":"all of which shared an ancestor seven million years ago,"},{"time":412789,"text":"but the genome of the mammoth shows it to share"},{"time":414878,"text":"a most recent common ancestor with Asian elephants"},{"time":417658,"text":"about six million years ago,"},{"time":419074,"text":"so slightly closer to the Asian elephant."}]},{"cues":[{"time":421547,"text":"With advances in ancient DNA technology,"},{"time":424271,"text":"we can actually now start to begin to sequence"},{"time":426224,"text":"the genomes of those other extinct mammoth forms that I mentioned,"},{"time":429535,"text":"and I just wanted to talk about two of them,"},{"time":431422,"text":"the woolly and the Columbian mammoth,"},{"time":433476,"text":"both of which were living very close to each other"},{"time":435894,"text":"during glacial peaks,"},{"time":438519,"text":"so when the glaciers were massive in North America,"},{"time":440682,"text":"the woollies were pushed into these subglacial ecotones,"},{"time":443277,"text":"and came into contact with the relatives living to the south,"},{"time":446488,"text":"and there they shared refugia,"},{"time":448500,"text":"and a little bit more than the refugia, it turns out."},{"time":450884,"text":"It looks like they were interbreeding."},{"time":453384,"text":"And that this is not an uncommon feature"},{"time":455017,"text":"in Proboscideans, because it turns out"},{"time":456655,"text":"that large savanna male elephants will outcompete"},{"time":459568,"text":"the smaller forest elephants for their females."},{"time":462936,"text":"So large, hairless Columbians"},{"time":465248,"text":"outcompeting the smaller male woollies."},{"time":467051,"text":"It reminds me a bit of high school, unfortunately."}]},{"cues":[{"time":469669,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":472008,"text":"So this is not trivial, given the idea that we want"},{"time":474702,"text":"to revive extinct species, because it turns out"},{"time":476907,"text":"that an African and an Asian elephant"},{"time":478727,"text":"can actually interbreed and have live young,"},{"time":480822,"text":"and this has actually occurred by accident in a zoo"},{"time":482963,"text":"in Chester, U.K., in 1978."},{"time":486005,"text":"So that means that we can actually take Asian elephant chromosomes,"},{"time":489151,"text":"modify them into all those positions we've actually now"},{"time":491309,"text":"been able to discriminate with the mammoth genome,"},{"time":493693,"text":"we can put that into an enucleated cell,"},{"time":496474,"text":"differentiate that into a stem cell,"},{"time":498733,"text":"subsequently differentiate that maybe into a sperm,"},{"time":501053,"text":"artificially inseminate an Asian elephant egg,"},{"time":503677,"text":"and over a long and arduous procedure,"},{"time":506784,"text":"actually bring back something that looks like this."},{"time":510293,"text":"Now, this wouldn't be an exact replica,"},{"time":511983,"text":"because the short DNA fragments that I told you about"},{"time":514465,"text":"will prevent us from building the exact structure,"},{"time":516946,"text":"but it would make something that looked and felt"},{"time":518482,"text":"very much like a woolly mammoth did."}]},{"cues":[{"time":521589,"text":"Now, when I bring up this with my friends,"},{"time":524333,"text":"we often talk about, well, where would you put it?"},{"time":526941,"text":"Where are you going to house a mammoth?"},{"time":528629,"text":"There's no climates or habitats suitable."},{"time":530669,"text":"Well, that's not actually the case."},{"time":532009,"text":"It turns out that there are swaths of habitat"},{"time":534902,"text":"in the north of Siberia and Yukon"},{"time":537237,"text":"that actually could house a mammoth."},{"time":538443,"text":"Remember, this was a highly plastic animal"},{"time":540688,"text":"that lived over tremendous climate variation."},{"time":543349,"text":"So this landscape would be easily able to house it,"},{"time":546231,"text":"and I have to admit that there [is] a part of the child in me,"},{"time":549891,"text":"the boy in me, that would love to see"},{"time":551176,"text":"these majestic creatures walk across the permafrost"},{"time":554022,"text":"of the north once again, but I do have to admit"},{"time":556477,"text":"that part of the adult in me sometimes wonders"},{"time":558621,"text":"whether or not we should."}]},{"cues":[{"time":561026,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":562711,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":567909,"text":"Ryan Phelan: Don't go away."},{"time":569426,"text":"You've left us with a question."},{"time":571158,"text":"I'm sure everyone is asking this. When you say, \"Should we?\""},{"time":574682,"text":"it feels like you're reticent there,"},{"time":577291,"text":"and yet you've given us a vision of it being so possible."},{"time":580269,"text":"What's your reticence?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":581595,"text":"Hendrik Poinar: I don't think it's reticence."},{"time":582901,"text":"I think it's just that we have to think very deeply"},{"time":586699,"text":"about the implications, ramifications of our actions,"},{"time":589250,"text":"and so as long as we have good, deep discussion"},{"time":591450,"text":"like we're having now, I think"},{"time":593466,"text":"we can come to a very good solution as to why to do it."},{"time":596172,"text":"But I just want to make sure that we spend time"},{"time":597809,"text":"thinking about why we're doing it first."}]},{"cues":[{"time":599658,"text":"RP: Perfect. Perfect answer. Thank you very much, Hendrik."}]},{"cues":[{"time":602439,"text":"HP: Thank you. (Applause)"}]}]}